[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Jan Clement for his thoughtful discussion of the differential diagnosis in this outbreak that involved 90 marines who were suspected to have contracted leptospirosis at the Jungle Warfare Training Center, Camp Gonsalves in Northern Okinawa, Japan (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camp_Gonsalves). The diagnosis of leptospirosis was said to be confirmed in more than half of cases, although the methods used to confirm this diagnosis were not specified in the news report. Also, the news report did not say if other diagnoses, such as scrub typhus or hemorrhagic fever with renal syndrome, were considered and ruled out. ProMED-mail would appreciate receiving additional information in this regard from knowledgeable sources.

The news report said that 3 marines had their gallbladders removed and Dr Clements raises the issue of acute acalculous cholecystitis (AAC) in these patients. AAC is a severe illness that that develops in the setting of various other conditions in critically ill patients. The usual finding on imaging studies is a distended acalculous gallbladder with thickened walls (greater than 3-4 mm) with or without pericholecystic fluid. Gangrene and perforation of the gallbladder can complicate AAC. The primary therapy for AAC has been cholecystectomy, but percutaneous cholecystostomy is gaining acceptance as an alternative. For a discussion of AAC, see http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK6881/.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2958645,25112. - Mod.ML]
